SIMPLE: transposition
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Transposition
<hw>Trans`po*si"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>transposition</ets>, from L. <ets>transponere</ets>,
<ets>transpositum</ets>, to set over, remove, transfer; <ets>trans</ets>
across, over + <ets>ponere</ets> to place. See <er>Position</er>.]</ety>
<def>The act of transposing, or the state of being transposed.</def>
Specifically: --⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Alg.)</fld> <def>The bringing of any term of an
equation from one side over to the other without destroying the
equation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>A change of the natural order of
words in a sentence; as, the Latin and Greek languages admit
<xex>transposition</xex>, without inconvenience, to a much greater
extent than the English.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(c)</sd> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A change of a composition into
another key.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transpositional</ent>⟦br⟧
